Programmed: True means the Gateway controller (NGF, in this case) has actually finished the work of turning your Gateway spec into a real, running data-plane — not just validating the YAML.
What "Accepted" vs "Programmed" actually mean
These are two separate condition checks Gateway API defines, and they happen in sequence:
Accepted: True — the controller has looked at your Gateway spec and confirmed it's syntactically valid and semantically sensible (valid gatewayClassName, valid listener config, no conflicting ports, etc.). This just means "I understand what you're asking for and I'm willing to try."
Programmed: True — the controller has gone further and actually provisioned the real infrastructure to make that Gateway work: in NGF's case, this means it has created the data-plane NGINX Deployment and its Service, and that Service has been assigned a real address. This is confirmed by the fact that your output already shows:
yamlstatus:
  addresses:
  - type: IPAddress
    value: 103.232.25.197
That's a strong signal a real Service/IP now exists behind this Gateway — which means, unlike a moment ago, the data-plane pod and LoadBalancer Service should now actually be present.
So — go check now
bashkubectl get pods -n nginx-gateway -o wide
kubectl get svc -n nginx-gateway
You should now see the public-gateway-nginx Deployment/pod and a LoadBalancer type Service with EXTERNAL-IP matching 103.232.25.197.
One more detail worth noting from your output
yaml- lastTransitionTime: ...
  reason: NoConflicts
  status: "False"
  type: Conflicted
Conflicted: False is actually the good outcome here — it means there are no conflicts on this listener (the condition name is Conflicted, and its status being False means that condition is not true, i.e. no conflict exists). Also notice attachedRoutes: 0 — that's expected right now since you haven't applied an HTTPRoute yet; that count will go to 1 once you create one.
